          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Low-level hardware events of this type are referred to as Quartz events. A typical event in macOS originates when the user manipulates an input device such as a mouse or a keyboard. The device driver associated with that device, through the I/O Kit, creates a low-level event, puts it in the window serverâ€™s event queue, and notifies the window server. The window server creates a Quartz event, annotates the event, and dispatches the event to the appropriate run-loop port of the target process. There the event is picked up by the Carbon Event Manager and forwarded to the event-handling mechanism appropriate to the application environment. You can use event taps to gain access to Quartz events at several different steps in this process.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "This opaque type is derived from CFType and inherits the properties that all Core Foundation types have in common. For more information, see ",
              "type": "text"
            },
